{{Licensing of patents}}
The '''Defensive Patent License''' ('''DPL''') is a [[patent license]] proposed by Jason Schultz and Jennifer Urban, directors of the [[Samuelson Law, Technology & Public Policy Clinic]] at the [[University of California, Berkeley]] as a [[patent licensing]] equivalent of the [[GPL]] copyright license.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.networkworld.com/community/node/60939|title=The Defensive Patent License makes patents less evil for open source|publisher=[[Network World]]|author=Julie Bort|date=2010-05-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fosspatents.blogspot.com/2010/05/will-defensive-patent-license-be-able.html|title=Will the Defensive Patent License be able to make patents 'less evil' for Free and Open Source Software? |publisher=FOSS Patents|author=[[Florian Müller (author)|Florian Mueller]]|date=May 17, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ttB_mjcIKcY|title=A Defensive Patent License Proposal |publisher=[[Stanford Center for Internet and Society]]/[[YouTube]]|author=Schultz and Urban |date=May 10, 2011}}</ref>

It requires entities licensing their patents under the DPL to license all of their patents under the DPL, with free licenses granted to all other DPL participants.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2012/06/defensive-patent-license-created-to-protect-innovators-from-trolls/|title="Defensive Patent License" created to protect innovators from trolls|publisher=[[Ars Technica]]|author=Jon Brodkin|date=June 12, 2012}}</ref> DPL participants remain free to launch patent lawsuits against non-participants.

DPL 1.0<ref>http://www.defensivepatentlicense.com/content/defensive-patent-license</ref> was published on November 16, 2013, and a "birthday" celebration held at the [[Internet Archive]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.archive.org/2013/11/13/birthday-of-the-defensive-patent-license-friday-nov-15-430-800-in-sf/|title=Birthday of the Defensive Patent License: Friday, Nov 15, 4:30-8:00 in SF|date=November 15, 2013}}</ref> The Internet Archive was designated as the fiscal umbrella organization until it has its own non-profit entity.  It was launched on February 28, 2014 at a conference in Berkeley.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.defensivepatentlicense.org/content/frequently-asked-questions|title = DPL FAQ}}
</ref>

