The '''Middle Bronze Age Cold Epoch''' was a period of unusually cold climate in the [[North Atlantic]] region, lasting from about 1800 BC to about 1500 BC.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Siklosy |first=Z. |authorlink= |year=2007 |title=Middle bronze age climate change recorded in a Hungarian stalagmite: triggering by volcanic activity? |journal=Geophysical Research Abstracts |volume=11 |issue=00777 |pages= |doi= |url=http://www.cosis.net/abstracts/EGU2007/00777/EGU2007-J-00777.pdf |accessdate= |quote= |display-authors=etal}}</ref> It was followed by the Bronze Age Optimum (1500—900 BC).
[[File:Greenland gisp2 alley.png|thumb|340px|Central Greenland reconstructed temperature.]]
During that epoch, a series of severe [[Volcano|volcanic]] eruptions occurred, including [[Mount Vesuvius]] ([[Avellino eruption]], about 1660 BC),<ref>{{cite journal | author = Vogel, J. S.| year = 1990 | title = Vesuvius/Avellino, one possible source of seventeenth century BC climatic disturbances | journal = [[Nature (journal)|Nature]] | volume = 344 | issue = 6266 | pages = 534–537 | doi = 10.1038/344534a0 |bibcode = 1990Natur.344..534V |display-authors=etal}}</ref> [[Mount Aniakchak]] (about 1645 BC),<ref>{{cite journal | quotes =  | author = Pearce, N. J. G., J. A. Westgate, S. J. Preece, W. J. Eastwood, and W. T. Perkins | year = 2004 | title = Identification of Aniakchak (Alaska) tephra in Greenland ice core challenges the 1645 BC date for Minoan eruption of Santorini | journal = Geochem. Geophys. Geosyst. | volume = 5 | issue =  3| doi = 10.1029/2003GC000672 | pages =  Q03005 | bibcode=2004GGG.....5.3005P}}</ref> and [[Santorini|Thera]] ([[Minoan eruption]], about 1620 BC).<ref>{{cite journal| last=Friedrich|first=Walter L.|authorlink=|title=Santorini Eruption Radiocarbon Dated to 1627-1600 B.C.|journal=Science|volume=312|issue=5773|pages=548|year=2006|doi=10.1126/science.1125087 |accessdate=| pmid=16645088|display-authors=etal}}</ref>

